[{"id":"VH934014","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents two polar curves in the x y coordinate plane, with the origin labeled O. The first polar curve begins at the origin and moves upward and to the right briefly, before turning upward and to the left and crossing the y axis above the origin. It continues upward and to the left until it reaches a maximum to the left of the y axis and above the x axis. It then moves downward and to the left, crosses the x axis to the left of the origin, before turning downward and to the right. It reaches a minimum to the left of the y axis and below the x axis, directly below its maximum. It then moves upward and to the right, and crosses the y axis below the origin, before turning upward and to the left, and ending at the origin where it began. The second polar curve begins on the x axis, far to the right of the origin. It moves upward and to the left until it reaches a maximum to the right of the y axis and above the x axis. It then moves downward and to the left, and intersects the first polar curve on the y axis, above the origin. It continues downward and to the left and crosses the x axis just to the left of the origin, before turning downward and to the right. It continues downward and to the right, and intersects the first polar curve for the second time, on the y axis below the origin. It reaches a minimum at a point to the right of the y axis and below the x axis, directly below its maximum. The curve then moves upward and to the right until it ends on the x axis at the point where it began.\" height=\"251\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH934014.g03.png\" width=\"300\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The graph above shows the polar curves <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r equals, 2 plus cosine theta\"><math alttext=\"r equals, 2 plus cosine theta\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r equals, 2 minus, 2 times cosine theta\"><math alttext=\"r equals, 2 minus, 2 times cosine theta\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>cos</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Which of the following expressions gives the area of the region that is inside both polar curves?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH934014_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"one half times the integral from 0 to 2 pi, of, open parenthesis, 3 times cosine theta, close parenthesis, squared, d theta\"><math alttext=\"one half times the integral from 0 to 2 pi, of, open parenthesis, 3 times cosine theta, close parenthesis, squared, d theta\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mo>∫</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi></mrow></msubsup><mrow><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>cos</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi>d</mi><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mrow></mstyle></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"one half times the integral from 0 to 2 pi, of, open parenthesis, open parenthesis, 2 plus cosine theta, close parenthesis, squared, minus, open parenthesis, 2 minus, 2 times cosine theta, close parenthesis, squared, close parenthesis, d theta\"><math alttext=\"one half times the integral from 0 to 2 pi, of, open parenthesis, open parenthesis, 2 plus cosine theta, close parenthesis, squared, minus, open parenthesis, 2 minus, 2 times cosine theta, close parenthesis, squared, close parenthesis, d theta\" overflow=\"scroll\"><m